description.value: Fragment of a larger clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows a darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. On the rear an impression probably from the rim of a vessel, inside impressions of some plant remains, probably as a stopper. The front side of the sealing is shaped slightly convex with many finger impressions and a part that was smoothed, probably with fingers. One complete seal impression and part of a second next to it are preserved from an oval scarab-like seal. The complete example is covered by a finger impression distorting the motif. It looks like three figures in the top, the one on the right seems to be a seated baboon, facing towards the left. Underneath small hieroglyphic sings, maybe an eye on top of strokes on the left and something like mr and nb underneath of the baboon. Black accretion on both sides.

description.value: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a a flat surface with imprints of some organics, probably wood? One impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2cm is visible in the break. The upper side is flat. Less than two thirds of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two registers, the upper one shows three figures, the one on the left side seems to be seated, maybe Re-Harakhte, the middle one looks mummy-shaped with a staff in front of the body, probably Ptah. The figure on the right shows a standing female goddess also holding a staff in front of her, probably Sekhmet. The lower register shows half of a kneeling figure with the hands raised (C11). The same motif is found on EA86904 with the right part of the impression better preserved.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression showing impressions of one convex coil of basketry on one side, probably the rim, and another coil of basketry on the second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The front shows an almost complete impression of a scarab-like seal with disturbance in the middle part of the seal, few finger impressions around it.  At the top right corner a small hole through the seal, maybe originally from a string. The seal impression is cut very sharply and shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. Visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. Behind him on the right a seated lion with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. Underneath a bound captive, lying on his belly, with his hands and feet bound backwards, not completely preserved. The same motif … (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Knob-shaped object made of fine brown Nile clay. The base is round and very flat, it was pressed onto a flat surface to form it. The upper side shows a central area that is raised with concave sides running upwards from the base and forms a cylindrical part with a shallow indentation in the middle to attach another object. The base is partly chipped off, partly was it not formed perfectly round. Some sort of stand or knob. Some white accretion on the surface.

description.value: Clay disc made of Nile clay with quite a lot voids from organic temper. The clay was fired and is very hard and might therefore be overfired or originate from the core of a sherd. The object was shaped into a round and flat disc with a lot of scratches on one surface that was well smoothed as well as on the edges. The other side shows two incised parallel line, one through the centre and another close to the edge of the object. In the middle with the incised line a thin crack can be seen. The object is pierced in the middle, over two thirds of the perforation were drilled from one side before the object was turned over. The perforation has an inner diameter of 0.7 cm, an outer diameter of 1.0 cm.  Possible use as a spindle whorl.

description.value: Irregular bulla made of a fine brown Nile clay in the shape of a ball. The object is very roughly formed and finished, the surface is irregular as well as very eroded and partly chipped off, there are white accretions as well as black discolouration on the surface. There are five possibly six seal impressions of an oval scarab-like seal with a very flat cut motif that is almost unrecognisable anymore. One of the impressions shows a circumferential line with two signs, a straight thick line as well as a sign that consists of two perpendicular bands meeting in a right angle (L-shape). The seal has the size of about 1.2 x 1.0 cm. After excavation a glossy translucent substance was added for consolidation.

description.value: Baked clay sealing with seal-impression: this is part of a jar-stopper. The seal impression shows the king Shabako subduing an enemy, he lifts a short sword in his right(?) arm holding in his other arm an enemy whos representation has broken away. He is also holding a flail in this hand. Above in front of the king is a hieroglyphic inscription. The "action" referred to in the inscription is the whole of the ritual acts of the of which the ceremonial slaughter of the enemy was part. Behind the king there is another hieroglyphic inscription. To the left of the cartouche then a group of damaged hieroglyphs. Back shows mark otherwise smooth. Incomplete; worn. Deposit.

description.value: Blue glass intaglio with a portrait of Cleopatra VII: this pale blue glass gem shows a portrait of a royal woman, identified by the broad, knotted diadem. The hair is tied back in a bun in the usual Greek manner and the dress that the queen wears is also Greek in origin, with folds of drapery clearly visible. The headdress, however, is Egyptian in style and in the form of a triple uraeus; the cobras wear sun discs on their heads. The portrait features are relatively clear and show a full face, with straight nose and a strong chin with a downturned mouth. It is, however, the hairstyle and broad diadem in particular that indicate that this representation is of Cleopatra VII. Sardonyx intagio sealstone: the engraved design is of a draped, female bust, the hair bound by a double diadem formed by two strips worn close together but revealing the strands of hair in between. The hair is pulled back from the brow, and two rows of corkscrew locks frame the face, and then fall on to the shoulders. The eye that is shown is large. The downturned mouth and the short nose with flared nostrils compare with the marble portrait of a Ptolemaic queen which may represent Cleopatra II or III. The woman wears a garment that is pinned on her shoulder. The workmanship is fairly crude, but the composition is lively. Blue glass seal: the youth is shown with a prominent fringe of hair falling across the brow and temple; a long straight nose; small, angular chin; and the broad jaw and cheekbones that were to be such a strong feature of the portraits of Augustus. Beneath him is a cornucopia overflowing with fruit.
